    <p>If you live in central Indiana, you already know what summer does to your hair. The moment you step outside in June, July, or August, the humidity hits and every strand you carefully styled that morning starts to expand, puff, and frizz. It does not matter how much product you used or how long you spent with a flat iron — Indiana humidity is relentless, and it wins nearly every time.</p>

    <p>The good news is that professional smoothing treatments have come a long way. Today's options range from lightweight glosses that calm frizz for a few weeks to full keratin treatments that keep your hair smooth and manageable for months. Here is what our stylists at Glow Salon &amp; Spa recommend for surviving summer without fighting your hair every morning.</p>

    <h2>Why Indiana Humidity Causes Frizz in the First Place</h2>
    <p>Frizz happens when moisture in the air penetrates the outer layer of your hair shaft — the cuticle. When the cuticle is raised or damaged, it absorbs humidity unevenly, causing individual strands to swell and separate from the rest of your hair. The result is that puffy, undefined texture that no amount of smoothing serum seems to fix.</p>

    <p>Indiana averages 70 to 80 percent relative humidity during summer months. That is significantly higher than what most hair can handle without some kind of intervention. Clients with naturally wavy, curly, or color-treated hair tend to notice it more because their cuticle layers are already slightly lifted, but even people with straight hair deal with flyaways and loss of sleekness during our summers.</p>

    <h2>Keratin Treatments: The Gold Standard for Frizz Elimination</h2>
    <p>Keratin treatments are the most effective professional solution for summer frizz. They work by infusing a protein-based formula into the hair shaft and then sealing it with heat. The result is a smoother, flatter cuticle that repels moisture instead of absorbing it.</p>

    <p>What to expect from a keratin treatment at our salon:</p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>How long it takes:</strong> About two to three hours depending on your hair length and thickness</li>
        <li><strong>How long it lasts:</strong> Three to five months with proper care, which means one treatment can carry you through the entire Indiana summer</li>
        <li><strong>What it does:</strong> Eliminates up to 90 percent of frizz, reduces blow-dry time by half or more, and adds a noticeable shine</li>
        <li><strong>What it does not do:</strong> A modern keratin treatment does not make your hair pin-straight unless you want it to. You can still wear your natural wave or curl — it will just be smoother, more defined, and frizz-free</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Keratin treatments are ideal for clients who spend significant time styling their hair each morning and want dramatic results. If you are tired of re-straightening your hair every time you walk outside, this is the treatment that changes everything.</p>

    <h2>Smoothing Glosses: A Lighter Alternative</h2>
    <p>Not everyone needs or wants a full keratin treatment. Smoothing glosses are a lighter option that calms frizz, adds shine, and improves manageability without the same level of commitment. Think of a gloss as a frizz-reducing top coat for your hair.</p>

    <p>A smoothing gloss is a good fit if:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>Your frizz is moderate rather than severe</li>
        <li>You want to test the waters before committing to a full keratin treatment</li>
        <li>You have fine hair that might feel weighed down by a heavier treatment</li>
        <li>You want something quick — most glosses take under an hour</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The tradeoff is longevity. A gloss typically lasts three to six weeks rather than several months. For some clients, that is perfect — a single application in late May carries them through the worst of early summer, and they come back for a refresh in July if they need it.</p>

    <h2>Deep Conditioning Treatments: Building a Foundation</h2>
    <p>Smoothing treatments work best on healthy hair. If your hair is already dry or damaged from winter, color processing, or heat styling, a deep conditioning treatment before your smoothing service makes a significant difference in how well the treatment absorbs and how long the results last.</p>

    <p>Our stylists often recommend a bond-repair or hydrating treatment as a prep step, especially for clients who color their hair regularly. Healthy, well-conditioned hair holds smoothing treatments longer because the cuticle is in better shape to begin with. Think of it like priming a wall before painting — the foundation matters.</p>

    <h2>How to Make Your Smoothing Treatment Last All Summer</h2>
    <p>Professional treatments do the heavy lifting, but how you care for your hair at home determines whether your results last six weeks or six months. Here is what our stylists tell every client after a smoothing service:</p>

    <ol>
        <li><strong>Switch to a sulfate-free shampoo:</strong> Sulfates strip the treatment from your hair faster than anything else. A gentle, sulfate-free formula extends your results dramatically</li>
        <li><strong>Wait before washing:</strong> After a keratin treatment, wait 48 to 72 hours before your first wash. This gives the treatment time to fully bond to your hair</li>
        <li><strong>Reduce wash frequency:</strong> Every wash removes a small amount of the treatment. If you can stretch to every two or three days, your results will last noticeably longer</li>
        <li><strong>Use a silk or satin pillowcase:</strong> Cotton pillowcases create friction that roughens the cuticle over time. Silk or satin keeps everything smooth while you sleep</li>
        <li><strong>Avoid chlorine without protection:</strong> Pool water is one of the fastest ways to strip a keratin treatment. Wet your hair with clean water before swimming and use a leave-in conditioner as a barrier</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>When to Book Your Summer Smoothing Treatment</h2>
    <p>Timing matters. The best time to book a keratin or smoothing treatment for summer is late April through mid-May — right before the humidity really sets in. This gives you the full benefit of the treatment during the months you need it most. If you wait until July when you are already frustrated with your hair, you have already lost weeks of smooth, easy styling.</p>

    <p>That said, it is never too late. If you are reading this in the middle of June and your hair is already driving you crazy, booking now will still give you two to four months of relief through the rest of summer and into early fall.</p>

    <h2>Who Should Consider a Smoothing Treatment</h2>
    <p>Smoothing treatments are not just for people with curly or thick hair. Our clients who benefit most from these services include:</p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Anyone who blow-dries daily:</strong> A keratin treatment cuts drying time in half, saving you 15 to 20 minutes every morning</li>
        <li><strong>Clients with color-treated hair:</strong> Color processing raises the cuticle, making treated hair more susceptible to humidity. A smoothing treatment seals everything back down</li>
        <li><strong>People with fine, flyaway hair:</strong> A lightweight gloss tames flyaways and adds polish without weighing fine hair down</li>
        <li><strong>Anyone tired of fighting their hair in summer:</strong> If your morning routine involves re-styling halfway through the day because the humidity undid your work, that is exactly what these treatments solve</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What About At-Home Anti-Frizz Products?</h2>
    <p>Over-the-counter serums, creams, and sprays can help, but they work on the surface rather than changing the hair's structure. They are best used as a supplement to professional treatments rather than a replacement. A good anti-humidity spray over a keratin-treated base is the combination that keeps your hair looking salon-fresh even on the most oppressive August days in Indiana.</p>

    <p>Products our stylists recommend between treatments include lightweight leave-in conditioners, humidity-blocking sprays, and argan or marula oil applied to the ends. We can recommend specific products based on your hair type during your appointment.</p>

